#Text=Tabriz
#Text=Tabriz ( Persian : تبریز , Azerbaijani : Təbriz ) is the capital of East Azerbaijan province , in the Azerbaijan region of Iran .
#Text=It is a modern industrialized Iranian city with signs of civilization dating back 2,500 years .

#Text=Having some of most famous museums , holding some of the cultural events , and harboring a couple of the most prestigious Iranian universities , the city is considered a major hub for science and culture in Iran .
#Text=Tabriz was named by the Organization of Islamic Conference as the " city of the Islamic world tourism " for 2018 .

column1: #Text=People
#Text=The majority of the city 's population are Iranian Azerbaijanis , followed by Persians , Armenians , Assyrians , and other people of the Caucasus .
#Text=Geography
#Text=Situated at an altitude of 1,340 meters above sea level , 619 km northwest of Tehran , it was the second largest city in Iran until the late 1960s .
#Text=It is a former capital of Persia , and had a population of 1,400,000 according to 1992 census .
#Text=Tabriz is in a valley to the north of the long ridge of Mount Sahand .
#Text=The valley opens out into a plain that slopes down gently to the northern end of Lake Orumieh , 60 km to the west .

#Text=The 160-km long Aji , Chai or Talkheh River is the major river of the city , formed by merging of three smaller rivers , namely the Ab Nahand , Quri Chai , and Ojan Chai , all of which originate from the Sabalan Mountain and the heights in the southeastern part of the town .
#Text=The river and streams join the Orumieh Lake after passing through the valleys between the Sorkhband and Yekkeh Chin mountain north of Tabriz and Osku district .

#Text=Mehran River or Maidan Chai , also called Liqvan River , originates from the peaks between Karim and Sultan mountains overlooking the Liqvan village ( a major center of cheese production in Iran ) near Esparakhoun and Qeshlaq .
#Text=Its worst natural disadvantage , however , is its vulnerability to earthquakes , one of which utterly destroyed the city in 858 .
#Text=Rebuilt in a minor key , it was again devastated in 1041 , when more than 40,000 people lost their lives .
#Text=Climate
#Text=By virtue of its situation , Tabriz has a continental climate with low humidity ( average annual rain fall is 288 mm ) .
#Text=It has a modestly warm summer climate and a severely cold winter .
#Text=History
#Text=The town has a long and checkered history .

#Text=Although the early history of Tabriz is shrouded in legend and mystery , the town 's origins are believed to date back to distant antiquity , perhaps even before the Sassanian era ( 224-651 AD ) .
#Text=The oldest stone tablet with a reference to Tabriz is that of Sargon II , the Assyrian king .
#Text=The tablet refers to a place called Tauri Castle and Tarmkis .
#Text=The historians believe that this castle was situated on the site of the present Tabriz .
#Text=It was the capital of Azarbin the 3rd century AD and again under the Mongol Ilkhanid dynasty ( 1256-13 53 ) , although for some time Maragheh supplanted it .
#Text=During the reign of Aqa Khan of the Ilkhanids , as well as under the reign of Ghazan Khan , Tabriz reached the peak of its glory and importance .
#Text=Many great artists and philosophers from all over the world traveled to Tabriz .
#Text=During this same period , Khajeh Rashid od-Din Fazlollah , the learned historian and Minister of Ghazan Khan , built the famous Rob'e Rashidi center .
#Text=In 1392 , after the end of Mongol rule , the town was sacked by Tamerlane .
#Text=It was soon restored under the Turkman tribe of the Qara Qoyunlu , who established a short-lived local dynasty .

#Text=Under the Safavids it rose from regional to national capital for a short period , but the second of the Safavid kings , Shah Tahmasb , moved the capital to Qazvin because of the vulnerability of Tabriz to Ottoman attacks .
#Text=The town then went into a period of decline , fought over by the Iranians , Ottomans and Russians and struck by earthquake and disease .
#Text=Tabriz was the residence of the crown prince under the Qajar kings , themselves of Turkish stock , but the town did not return to prosperity until the second half of the 19th century .

#Text=The greatest boost to Tabriz came with the opening up of Persia to the West at the turn of this century , when it became the main staging post between the interior of Iran and the Black Sea and , for a short time , the economic capital .
#Text=In 1908 it was the center of a revolt against Mohammad Ali Shah , which was only put down with the brutal intervention of the Russians .
#Text=In the second Irano-Russian War the city was occupied by the Tsar 's troops .
#Text=However , it was returned to Iran following the signing of the Turkmanchai Treaty , a peace and trade settlement that ended the Irano-Russian War of 1826-1828.
#Text=The Iranian Constitutional Revolution originated in Tabriz and culminated during the reign of Mohammad Ali Shah of Qajar dynasty ( 1779-1925 ) .
#Text=Sattar Khan and Baqer Khan were the two most prominent leading figures behind the movement .
#Text=Tabriz was occupied by Russians several times in the first half of the 20th century , including most of both world wars .

#Text=A railway line to the border at Jolfa , built by the expansionist Russians , has been of little importance , but it increased in significance in the 1990s as a result of Iran 's friendlier relations with its northern neighbors .
#Text=Talk

#Text=Azerbaijani , a Turkic language , is the primary language spoken by most Tabrizis , although many people , especially the younger generation , can communicate in Persian and moderate to advanced English .
#Text=Get in

#Text=Tabriz is 310 km southeast of Bazargan ( at the Iran — Turkey frontier ) , 159 km south of Jolfa on the Iran — Azerbaijan Republic border , and can be reached by road , rail ( 742 km from Tehran , with connections to Europe and Moscow ) , air from Tehran , Istanbul and other major cities in the region , and highway ( Highway number 1 connects Tabriz to Tehran ) .
#Text=By plane
#Text=Tabriz International Airport ( TBZ ) , Bolvar-e-Shahid Khalaban Babayi ( 10 km from the city center ) , ☏ +984115234705 .
#Text=This is a hub airport for Ata Airlines .
#Text=Airport bus #136 goes to airport from Motahhari St. every 30-40 minutes .
#Text=Another option is getting a taxi .
#Text=Ahwaz operated by Iran Air
#Text=Bandar Abbas operated by Iran Air
#Text=Isfahan operated by Iran Air
#Text=Mashhad operated by ATA air , Iran Air Tours , Iran Aseman and Zagros Airlines
#Text=Shiraz - Mon and Fri , operated by Iran Aseman .
#Text=Fare is 2,200,000 rials for 1-way .
#Text=Daily direct flights to Tehran ( Mehrabad Airport ) by Iran Air , Iran Aseman and other companies .
#Text=Fare is 490,000 rials for 1-way .
#Text=International direct flights to the following destinations exist :
#Text=Baghdad - F and M , operated by ATA air .
#Text=Baku - Tu and Sa , operated by Kish Air .
#Text=Damascus .
#Text=Dubai - Tu and Sa , operated by Kish Air ( around 200 USD for round trip ) .
#Text=Gaziantep - Tu , operated by Sky Airlines .
#Text=Istanbul
#Text=13 flights per week , operated by Turkish airlines ( 7 flights ) , Iran Air ( 2 flights ) and ATA air ( 4 flights ) .
#Text=Fare is around 250 USD for a round trip .
#Text=Tbilisi
